rticular canisters can be placed in any of 7 bases (not next to the 1st on the same side);No. of ways to place remaining 8 canisters on remaining 8 bases = 40 320;$$\\therefore$$ No. of ways to place the canisters; = 6 x 7 x 40 320 = 1 693 440;;$$\\therefore$$ Total no. of ways to place the canisters; = 1 290 240 + 1 693 440; = 2 983 680'),(1681,'200404003005','a) $$f(\\theta) = \\sin^{2}{\\theta} - 6 \\sin{\\theta} + 4 \\equiv (\\sin{\\theta} - 3)^{2} - 5$$;Deduce that $$f(\\theta)$$ is greatest when $$ \\sin{\\theta = -1} \\equiv (\\sin{\\theta} -3) = -4$$;i.e. $$f(\\theta)_{greatest} = (-4)^{2} -5 = 11$$;Deduce that $$f(\\theta)$$ is least when $$\\sin{\\theta} = 1 \\equiv (\\sin{\\theta} -3) = -2$$;i.e. $$f(\\theta)_{least} = (-2)^{2} -5 = -1$$;;b) ;$$\\begin{align} &\\sin{(A+B)} = 2 \\cos{(A-B)}\\\\;& \\Rightarrow \\sin{A} \\cos{B} + \\cos{A}\\sin{B} = 2(\\cos{A}\\cos{B} + \\sin{A}\\sin{B}) \\\\;&\\equiv \\frac{\\sin{A} \\cos{B}}{\\cos{A}\\cos{B} } + \\frac{\\cos{A}\\sin{B} }{\\cos{A}\\cos{B} } = 2\\left(1+\\frac{ \\sin{A}\\sin{B}}{\\cos{A}\\cos{B}}\\right)\\\\;& \\tan{A} + \\tan{B} = 2 + 2 \\tan{A}\\tan{B}\\\\;& \\frac{1}{3} + \\tan{B} = 2 + \\frac{2}{3} \\tan{B}\\\\;& \\left(1-\\frac{2}{3}\\right)\\tan{B} = 2 - \\frac{1}{3}\\\\;&\\therefore \\tan{B} = 5;\\end{align}$$'),(1682,'200404003023','Given $$P(A \\cup B)$$ = 0.9, $$P(A \\cap B)$$ = 0.2, and P(A|B) = 0.8.;;$$\\begin{align};& P(A \\cap B) = P(A | B).P(B) \\\\;& i.e. 0.2 = 0.8 P(B) \\\\;& \\Rightarrow P(B) = 0.25 \\\\;& P ( A \\cup B ) = P ( A ) + P ( B ) - P ( A \\cap B ) \\\\;& i.e. 0.9 = P(A) + 0.25 - 0.2 \\\\;& \\therefore P ( A ) = 0.85 \\\\;& P(B \\prime) = 1 - P(B) = 1 - 0.25 = 0.75\\\\;\\end{align}$$'),(1683,'200404003024','X~N($$\\mu$$,$$\\sigma^2$$);;As normal distribution are symmetrical,P ( X < 10 ) = P ( X > 20 ) ;$$\\begin{align};& \\Rightarrow \\mu(10 + 20)/2 = 15 \\\\ ;& P ( X > 20 ) = 0.330 \\\\ ;& \\equiv P(X < 20) = 1 - 0.330 = 0.669 \\\\ ;& \\equiv P ( Z < \\frac{20 - 15}{\\sigma^2} ) = 0.669 \\\\ ;& \\Phi(\\frac{20 - 15}{\\sigma^2}) = 0.669 \\\\ ;& \\frac{20 - 15}{\\sigma^2} = \\Phi^{- 1} ( 0.669 ) = 0.437 \\\\ ;& \\sigma^2 = \\frac{20 - 15}{0.437}= 11.44 \\\\ ;& \\therefore \\sigma = 3.382 = 3.38 (3sf) \\\\;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};& E ( \\overline{X}) = E ( X ) = \\mu = 15 \\\\;& Var(\\overline{X}) = \\frac{Var(X)}{100}= \\frac{\\sigma^2}{100}= \\frac{11.44}{100} \\\\;& = 0.1144 = 0.114 (3sf);\\end{align}$$'),(1684,'200404003025','Let X = mass of an apple of variety A;Let Y = mass of an apple of variety B;X ~ N(0.125,0.022), Y ~ N(0.100,0.032);Let C = $$(X_{1}+ X_{2}+ X_{3}) + (Y_{1}+ Y_{2}+ Y_{3}+ Y_{4})$$;where $$X_{1}, X_{2}, X_{3}$$ are masses of 3 randomly chosen apples of variety A, and $$Y_{1}, Y_{2}, Y_{3}, Y_{4}$$ are masses of 4 randomly chosen apples of variety B.;$$\\begin{align};&Let \\mu_c = E (C) \\\\ ;&= E((X_1 + X_2 + X_3) -(Y_1 + Y_2 + Y_3 + Y_4)) \\\\ ;&= 3E ( X ) - 4E ( Y ) \\\\ ;&= 3(0.125) - 4(0.100) = - 0.025 \\\\ ;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};&Let \\sigma_c^2 = Var ( C ) \\\\ ;&= Var((X_1 + X_2 + X_3) -(Y_1 + Y_2 + Y_3 + Y_4)) \\\\ ;&= 3Var ( X ) + 4Var ( Y ) \\\\ ;&= 3({0.02}^2) + 4({0.03}^2) = 0.0048 \\\\;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};&C \\sim N ( \\mu_c , \\sigma_c^2 ) \\\\ ;&P((X_1 + X_2 + X_3) >(Y_1 + Y_2 + Y_3 + Y_4)) \\\\ ;&\\equiv P ( ( X_1 + X_2 + X_3 ) - ( Y_1 + Y_2 + Y_3 + Y_4 ) > 0 ) \\\\ ;&\\equiv P(C > 0) \\\\ ;&\\equiv P ( Z > \\frac{0 - \\mu_c}{\\sigma_c} ) = P ( Z > \\frac{0 - ( - 0.025 )}{\\sqrt{0.0048}} ) \\\\ ;&= P(Z > 0.3608) \\equiv 1 - \\Phi(0.3608) \\\\ ;&= 1 - 0.6410 = 0.3590 = 0.359 (3sf);\\end{align}$$'),(1685,'200404003026','Let $$p_{9} = 9^{th}$$ percentile of X;$$\\begin{align};& F( p_9 ) = 0.09 \\\\;& \\frac{1}{81}(p_9)^2 = 0.09 \\\\;& \\therefore p_9 = 2.7 ;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};& f(x) = \\frac{d}{dx} F(x) \\\\;& =  \\frac{d}{dx}[\\frac{1}{81} x^2 ] \\\\;&= \\frac{2}{81}x, for 0 \\leq x \\leq 9 \\\\;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};& E (\\sqrt{X}) = \\int^\\infty_{-\\infty} \\sqrt{x}f (x)dx \\\\;& =   \\int^9_0 \\sqrt{x} \\left( \\frac{2}{81}x \\right)dx, for 0 \\leq x \\leq 9 \\\\;& =   \\int^9_0 \\frac{2}{81} x^{3 / 2}dx \\\\;& = {\\left[ \\frac{4}{405} x^{5 / 2}\\right]}^9_0   = \\frac{12}{5}\\\\;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};& E ( X ) = \\int^\\infty_{- \\infty}x.f(x) dx \\\\;& = \\int^9_0 x(\\frac{2}{81}x) dx \\\\;& = \\int^9_0 \\frac{2}{81}x^2 dx \\\\;& = {[ \\frac{2}{243} x^3 ]}^9_0 = 6 \\\\;\\end{align}$$;$$\\begin{align};& Var(\\sqrt{X}) = E(X) - [ E(\\sqrt{X}) ]^2 \\\\;& = 6 - ( \\frac{12}{5} )^2 = 0.24 \\\\;\\end{align}$$'),(1686,'200404003027','A suitable model for the distribution of Y is uniform (or rectangular) distribution.;;Let M = total mass of batch = $$\\sum \\left(x_{i} + \\frac{y_{i}}{1000}\\right)$$;$$\\begin{align};& E(M) = E\\left[\\sum \\left(x_{i} + \\frac{y_{i}}{1000}\\right)\\right] \\\\;& =\\left(\\sum x_{i}\\right) + \\frac{E(\\sum y_{i})}{1000} \\\\;& =\\left(\\sum x_{i}\\right) + \\frac{60E(Y)}{1000} \\\\;\\end{align}$$;;$$\\begin{align};& Y \\sim U (0,1000) \\\\;& \\Rightarrow E(Y) = \\frac{1}{2}(0, 1000) = 500 \\\\;& \\therefore E(M) = (\\sum x_{i} ) + \\frac{60(500)}{1000} = (\\sum x_{i} ) + 30;\\end{align}$$;;Given Var(Y) = $$\\frac{10^{6}}{12}$$;$$P(\\left(\\sum x_{i}\\right)+30$$ within $$\\pm$$ 5kg of $$\\sum \\left(x_{i} + \\frac{y_{i}}{1000}\\right))$$;$$\\equiv$$ P(30 within $$\\pm$$ 5kg of $$\\frac{\\sum y_{i}}{1000}$$);$$\\equiv P\\left(25 < \\frac{\\sum y_{i}}{1000} < 35\\right)$$;;$$\\begin{align};& Let S = \\frac{\\sum y_{i}}{1000} \\\\;& E(S) = E\\left(\\frac{\\sum y_{i}}{1000}\\right) \\\\;& = \\frac{60E(Y)}{1000} \\\\;& = \\frac{60(500)}{1000} = 30 \\\\;& Var(S) = Var\\left(\\frac{\\sum y_{i}}{1000}\\right) \\\\;& = \\frac{60 Var(Y)}{{1000}^2} \\\\;& = \\frac{60\\left(\\frac{{10}^6}{12}\\right)}{{10}^6}= 5 \\\\;\\end{align}$$;;Since batch size (=60) is large, S ~ N(30,5) approximately. ;$$\\begin{align};& P ( 25 < \\frac{\\sum y_{i}}{1000} < 35 ) \\\\;& \\equiv P(25 < S < 35) \\\\;& \\equiv P\\left(\\frac{25 - 30}{\\sqrt{5}} < Z < \\frac{35 - 30}{\\sqrt{5}}\\right) \\\\;& = P(- \\sqrt{5}< Z < \\sqrt{5}) \\equiv 2 \\Phi(\\sqrt{5}) - 1 \\\\;& = 2\\Phi ( 2.236 ) - 1 = 2 ( 0.9873 ) - 1 \\\\;& = 0.9746 = 0.975 (3sf)\\\\;\\end{align}$$'),(1687,'200404003028','A condition is that the moths are caught at randomly scattered intervals.;;Let M = no. of moths caught in an evening ;Let $$\\lambda$$=E(M)=3.5;M ~ Po($$\\lambda$$);P(5 or more moths caught in an evening);P ( M $$\\geq$$ 5 ) ;$$\\equiv$$ 1 - P(M $$\\leq$$ 4) ;= 1 - [P(M=0) + P(M=1) + P(M=2) + P(M = 3) + P(M = 4)] ;= 1 - $$e^{- \\lambda} \\left[ \\frac{\\lambda^0}{0 !} + \\frac{\\lambda^1}{1 !} + \\frac{\\lambda^2}{2 !} + \\frac{\\lambda^3}{3 !} + \\frac{\\lambda^4}{4 !}\\right]$$ ;= 1 - $$e^{- 3.5} \\left[ 1 + 3.5 + \\frac{(3.5)^2}{2}+ \\frac{(3.5)^3}{6}+ \\frac{(3.5)^4}{24} \\right]$$ ;= 0.2746 = 0.275 (3sf);;Let B = $$M_1+M_2+M_3+M_4$$ where $$M_1, M_2, M_3, M_4$$ are no. of moths caught in 4 randomly chosen evenings. ;Let $$\\mu$$=E(B)=E($$M_1+M_2+M_3+M_4$$) = 4E(M) = 4(3.5) = 14.0;B ~ Po($$\\mu$$);Since $$\\mu$$(=14) $$\\geq$$ 10;B ~ N($$\\mu$$,$$\\mu$$) approximately;P( 18 or more caught in 4 evenings) ;P ( B $$\\geq$$ 18 ) ;$$\\equiv$$ P(B > 17.5) ;$$\\equiv$$ P$$\\left(Z > \\frac{17.5 - \\lambda}{\\sqrt{\\lambda}}\\right)$$;= P$$\\left(Z > \\frac{17.5 - 14}{\\sqrt{14}}\\right)$$;= P$$(Z > 0.9354) \\equiv 1 - \\Phi (0.935)$$;= 1 - 0.8251 = 0.175 (3sf)'),(1688,'200404003029','a) The procedure does not gives a random sample because the children do not have equal chances of being selected.;;b) ;Let n = sample size = 50;Let $$p_0$$ = assume p = 0.8 and $$q_0$$ = 1 - $$p_0$$ = 0.2;Let $$p_s$$ = sample p = $$\\frac{34}{50}$$ = 0.68 and $$q_s$$ = 1- $$p_s$$ = 0.32;;Test $$H_0: p = p_0$$ against $$H_1: p < p_0$$ a 1 tailed test for less;The 5% critical value, $$z_{0.05}$$ = 1.645 ;Reject $$H_0$$ if $$z < -z_{0.05}$$;Under $$H_0$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \\frac{p_s - p_0}{\\sqrt{p_0 q_0 / n}} = \\frac{0.68 - 0.8}{\\sqrt{( 0.8 ) ( 0.2 ) / 50}} = - 2.12$$;Since $$z < -z_{0.05}$$, reject $$H_0$$ and conclude that at the 5% level of significance, there is sufficient evidence that the proportion of children at the school with access to a computer at home is less than 0.8.;;$$z_{0.025} \\sqrt{\\frac{p_s q_s}{n}} = 1.960\\sqrt{\\frac{( 0.68 ) ( 0.32 )}{50}} = 0.1293$$;A symmetric 95% confidence interval;$$p_s - z_{0.025} \\sqrt{\\frac{p_s q_s}{n}} , p_s + z_{0.025} \\sqrt{\\frac{p_s q_s}{n}}$$  ;= [ 0.68 - 0.1293, 0.68 + 0.1293 ] ;= [ 0.5507 , 0.8093 ] ;= [ 0.551, 0.809 ] (3sf)');
INSERT INTO `dbmanagement_solution` VALUES (1689,'200404003030','(i) Tabulate all possible products:;img;Tabulate frequency / probability distribution:;img;;$$E(X) = \\sum_{all x_{i}} x_{i}.P(X = x) $$;$$= (1)\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) + (2)\\left(\\frac{12}{36}\\right) + (3)\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) + (4)\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) + (6)\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) $$;$$= 3$$;;$$E(X^{2}) = \\sum_{all x_{i}} {x_{i}}^{2}.P(X = x) $$;$$= (1)^{2}\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) + (2)^{2}\\left(\\frac{12}{36}\\right) + (3)^{2}\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) + (4)^{2}\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right) + (6)^{2}\\left(\\frac{6}{36}\\right)$$;$$= \\frac{35}{3}$$;;$$\\therefore Var(X) = E(X^{2}) - [E(X)]^{2}$$;$$ = \\left(\\frac{35}{3}\\right) - (3)^{2} = \\frac{8}{3}$$;;(ii) ;Let n = sample size = 100;Let p = P(X = 2) = $$\\frac{12}{36}$$ = $$\\frac{1}{3}$$ and q = 1 - p = $$\\frac{2}{3}$$;T ~ B(n,p);Since n(= 100) is large and np$$\\left(= \\frac{100}{3}\\right)$$ > 5 and nq$$\\left(= \\frac{200}{3}\\right)$$ > 5;X ~ N(np, npq) = N $$\\left(\\frac{100}{3}, \\frac{200}{9}\\right)$$ approximately ;P(T $$\\geq$$ 40);$$\\equiv$$ P(T > 39.5) $$\\leftarrow$$ continuity correction;$$\\equiv$$ P$$\\left(Z > \\frac{39.5 - np}{\\sqrt{npq}}\\right)$$ = P $$\\left(Z > \\frac{39.5-\\frac{100}{3}}{\\sqrt{\\frac{200}{9}}} \\right)$$;= P(Z > 1.3081) = 1 - $$\\Phi$$(1.308);= 1 - 0.9045 = 0.0955(3sf)'),(1690,'200404003031','(i) ;Let n = sample size = 50;Let $$\\mu_{0}$$ = assume $$\\mu$$ = 9.5;Let $$\\sigma^{2}$$ = Var(X) = 15;;$$\\hat{\\mu} = \\overline{x} = \\frac{\\sum x}{n} = \\frac{527.1}{50} = 10.542$$;Test $$H_{0}: \\mu = \\mu_{0}$$ against $$H_{1}: \\mu \\neq \\mu_{0}$$ a 2-tailed test for difference;At 5% significance level, critical value $$z_{0.025}$$ = 1.960;Reject $$H_{0}$$ if $$\\left| z \\right| > \\left| z_{0.025} \\right|$$;Under $$H_{0}$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \\left( \\frac{\\overline{x} - \\mu_{0}}{\\sigma / \\sqrt{n}} \\right) = \\frac{10.542 - 9.5}{\\sqrt{15/50}} = 1.902$$;;Since $$\\left| z \\right| < \\left| z_{0.025} \\right|$$, do not reject $$H_{0}$$ and conclude that, at the 5% significance level, there is insufficient evidence that $$\\mu \\neq 9.5$$;;(ii);Let $$\\mu_{1}$$ = alternative assume $$\\mu = 11.5$$;With $$\\hat{\\mu}(= 10.542) < \\mu_{1}(= 11.5)$$, in a 1-tailed test with $$H_{0}: \\mu < \\mu_{1}$$;$$\\hat{\\sigma}^{2} = \\frac{1}{n-1}\\left[\\sum x^{2} - \\frac{1}{n}\\left(\\sum x\\right)^{2}\\right]$$;= $$\\frac{1}{49}\\left[6172.31 - \\frac{1}{50}\\left(527.1\\right)^{2}\\right]$$ = 12.56;For a 1-tailed test, the $$\\alpha$$% critical value is $$z_{\\alpha}$$;Under $$H_{0}$$, the test statistic is ;$$z = \\left( \\frac{\\overline{x} - \\mu_{1}}{\\sigma / \\sqrt{n}} \\right) = \\frac{10.542 - 11.5}{\\sqrt{12.56/50}} = -1.911$$;$$H_{0}$$ is accepted if $$z > - z_{\\alpha}$$;;i.e. -1.911 > -$$z_{\\alpha}$$;$$z_{\\alpha}$$ > 1.911;$$\\equiv \\Phi(z_{\\alpha}) > \\Phi(1.911)$$ ;$$\\equiv 1 - \\alpha > 0.9720$$;$$\\therefore \\alpha < 0.028$$;$$\\equiv$$ Significance level of test < 2.8%'),(1691,'200503003001','$$\\theta = 30^{\\circ}$$ is a root of $$2 - \\cos ^{2}\\theta = \\lambda \\cos 2\\theta$$;$$\\Rightarrow 2 - \\cos^{2}30^{\\circ} = \\lambda \\cos 2(30^{\\circ})$$;$$2 - \\left(\\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}\\right)^{2}  = \\frac{1}{2} \\lambda$$;$$\\Rightarrow \\lambda = \\frac{5}{2}$$;$$\\therefore$$ Equation is:;$$2 - \\cos^{2}\\theta = \\frac{5}{2} \\cos 2 \\theta $$;$$4 - 2 \\cos^{2}\\theta = \\frac{5}{2} ( 2 \\cos^{2} \\theta - 1)$$;$$2 \\ cos^{2} \\theta = 9$$;$$\\cos^{2}\\theta = \\frac{3}{4}$$;$$\\cos\\theta = \\pm \\frac{\\sqrt{3}}{2}$$;$$\\theta = 360 n^{\\circ} \\pm 30^{\\circ}$$ or $$360 n^{\\circ} \\pm 150^{\\circ}$$;For $$0^{\\circ} \\leq \\theta \\leq 360^{\\circ}$$, besides $$\\theta = 30^{\\circ}, \\theta= 150^{\\circ} ,210^{\\circ}$$ or $$330^{\\circ}$$'),(1692,'200503003002','$$1 + \\left | 2x -3  \\right | = 3x \\Rightarrow \\left | 2x -3  \\right | = 3x -1$$;;For $$2x - 3 > 0 \\Rightarrow x > 