75 \\leq Z \\leq 1.15179);\\\\ = \\Phi(1.518)-[1-\\Phi(0.778)];\\\\ = 0.9355-[1-0.7817];\\\\ = 0.7172 = 0.717(3dp)\\end{align}$$;;(ii) ;Let u represent the number of people who have gene B out of a random sample of 1000 $$\\Rightarrow$$ U ~ B(1000,.003);Since n=1000 is large and np = 3<10, U ~ Po(3) approximately;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that at least 2 but fewer than 5 have gene B;$$\\begin{align} = P(2 \\leq U < 5);\\\\ = P(U=2) + P(U=3) + P(U=4);\\\\ = e^{-3}\\left[\\frac{(3)^2}{2!}+\\frac{(3)^3}{3!} + \\frac{(3)^4}{4!}\\right];\\\\ = 0.616(3dp)\\end{align}$$'),(1765,'200704003007','Let X represent the time in hours taken by a student to complete a project, with population mean $$\\mu$$.;$$\\therefore$$ Unbiased estimate of mean, $$\\mu$$;$$\\begin{align} = \\overline{x} = \\frac{\\sum x}{n} = \\frac{4626}{150} = 30.84\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ Unbiased estimate of population variance, $$s^2$$;$$\\begin{align} =\\frac{1}{150-1}\\left[147691-\\frac{4626^2}{150}\\right];\\\\ = \\frac{5025.16}{149} = 33.7(3sf) \\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ To test if the population mean time for a student to complete the project exceeds 30 hours at 5% significance level,;Test $$H_0: \\mu = 30$$ against $$H_1:\\mu>30$$;One-tail test at 5% significance level, $$\\alpha = 0.05$$;Under $$H_0$$, since $$n=150$$ is large, by Central Limit Theorem, $$\\overline{X} ~ N(30, \\frac{33.7}{150})$$ approximately, where $$\\overline{X}$$ is the sample means.;Perform Z-test with: $$\\mu_0 = 30, s = \\sqrt{33.7259}, \\overline{x} = 30.84$$ and $$n=150$$.;From GC, p-value = 0.0382;Since p-value = 0.0382 < 0.05, we reject $$H_0$$ and conclude that there is sufficient evidence at the 5% significance level that the mean time for a student to complete the project exceeds 30hours.;;$$\\therefore$$ No assumption is needed in order for the test to be valid because since sample size is large, by Central Limit Theorem, the sample mean is approximately normally distributed.'),(1766,'200704003008','(i) ;Let C and T represent mass of a randomly chosen chicken and turkey respectively, in kg $$\\Rightarrow \\space C \\sim N(2.2,0.5^2), T\\sim N(10.5,2.1^2)$$;;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that a randomly chosen chicken costs more than $7;$$\\begin{align} = P(3C > 7);\\\\ = P\\left(C > \\frac{7}{3}\\right) ;\\\\ = P\\left(Z > \\frac{\\frac{7}{3} - 2.2}{0.5}\\right) ;\\\\ = P(Z > 0.2667);\\\\ = 1- \\Phi(0.267);\\\\ = 0.3947 = 0.395(3dp)\\end{align}$$;;(ii) ;The probability that a randomly chosen turkey costs more than $55 ;$$\\begin{align} = P(5T > 55);\\\\ = P\\left(T > \\frac{55}{5}\\right) ;\\\\ = P\\left(Z > \\frac{11-10.5}{2.1}\\right);\\\\ = P(Z > 0.2381);\\\\ = 1-\\Phi(0.238);\\\\ = 0.4059\\end{align}$$;;$$\\therefore$$ Probability that both a random chicken costs more than $7 and random turkey costs more than $55;$$\\begin{align} =  P(C > \\frac{7}{3}) \\times P(T > 11);\\\\ = 0.347 \\times 0.4059;\\\\ = 0.1602 = 0.160 (2dp)\\end{align}$$;;(iii);Let Y be the cost of 3 chickens and 5 turkeys;Y = 3C + 5T;Y~N$$\\left(3(2.2) + 5(10.5), 3^2(0.5^2)+5^2(2.1^2) \\right)$$;$$\\Rightarrow$$ Y~N(59.1,112.5);;$$\\therefore$$ The probability that the total selling price of a randomly chosen chicken and a randomly chosen turkey is more than $62;$$\\begin{align} = P(Y > 62);\\\\ = P\\left(Z > \\frac{62-59.1}{\\sqrt{112.5}}\\right) ;\\\\ = P(Z > 0.2734);\\\\ = 1 - \\Phi(0.273);\\\\ = 0.3924 = 0.392(2dp)\\end{align}$$;;(iv) ;The reason why the answer to part (iii) is greater than the answer to part(ii) is because the condition for the total selling price of chicken and turkey exceeds $62[part(iii)] is less restrictive than the condition for the selling price of chicken is greater than $7 and at the same time, the selling price of turkey is greater than $55[part(ii)]'),(1767,'200704003009','(i);a) The number of different possible arrangement = 12! = 479001600;b) The number of different possible orders in which each man stands next to his wife  = 6! x $$(2^6)$$ = 46080;(