s: Solve $$D(x) = 0$$  \r;(b) Horizontal Asymptotes: \r;If degree of $$N(x)$$ < degree of $$D(x)$$, then y = 0 else If degree of $$N(x)$$ = degree of $$D(x)$$, divide out to get $$\\frac{N(x)}{D(x)} = h + \\frac{n(x)}{D(x)}$$ and $$y = h$$ is the horizontal asymptote  \r;If degree of $$N(x)$$ > degree of $$D(x)$$, divide out to get $$\\frac{N(x)}{D(x)} = p(x) + \\frac{n(x)}{D(x)}$$ and if $$p(x) = mx + c$$ is linear function then $$y = mx + c$$ is the horizontal asymptote  '),(314,'Parametric Equations','C',1,'Representations such as $$x = g(t)$$ and $$y = h(t)$$ are known as Parametric Equations and $$t$$ is the Parameter'),(315,'Special Graphs - Type 1','C',1,'The graphs of $$y = |f(x)|$$ and $$y = f(|x|)$$ are transformations of the graph  $$y = f(x)$$'),(316,'Special Graphs - Type 2','C',1,'Graph $$y^2 = f(x)$$ is a transformation of the graph $$y = f(x)$$ as follows: $$y^2 = f(x) \\implies y = \\sqrt{f(x)}$$ or $$y = -\\sqrt{f(x)}$$ '),(317,'Special Graphs - Type 3','C',1,'Graph $$y = \\frac{1}{f(x)}$$ is a transformation of the graph $$y = f(x)$$'),(318,'One - One Function','C',5,'Given a function $$f : x \\mapsto f(x), x  \\in X$$: $$f$$ is a one-one function $$\\iff$$ the rule $$x \\mapsto f(x)$$ of the function $$f$$ is a One-one Relation for all $$x \\in X$$ '),(319,'Restriction to One-one Function','C',5,'Given a function $$f : x \\mapsto f(x), x  \\in X$$ which is not one-one, the domain $${D}_{f} = X$$ can be restricted in such a way that its restriction $${f}_{R}$$ : $$x \\mapsto f(x), x \\in {X}_{R}$$ is one-one'),(320,'Inverse Function','C',5,'Given a function $$f : x \\mapsto f(x), x  \\in X$$ with $${D}_{f} = X$$ and $${R}_{f} = Y$$, its Inverse Function is $${f}^{-1}$$ : $$y \\mapsto x, y \\in Y$$ with $${D}_{f^{-1}} = Y$$ and $${R}_{f^{-1}} = X$$ exists $$\\iff$$ $$f$$ is one-one'),(321,'Composite Function','C',5,'Given two functions: $$f$$ : $$x \\mapsto f(x), x \\in {X}_{f}$$ and $$g$$ : $$x \\mapsto g(x), x \\in {X}_{g}$$, the composite function $$g \\circ f$$ : $$x \\mapsto g(f(x)), x \\in {X}_{f}$$'),(322,'Polynomial Inequality','C',6,'Given an inequality: $$g(x) > h(x)$$ \r;(i) Rearrange $$g(x) > h(x)$$ into its Homogenous Form: $$f(x) > 0$$ or $$f(x) < 0$$ \r;(ii) Factorise $$f(x)$$ completely into Linear Factors : $$(ax + b)(cx + d)... > 0$$ \r;(iii) For each Linear Factor, find Critical Value: $$ ax + b = 0 \\implies x = -\\frac{b}{a}$$ \r;(iv) Mark all critical values on a Number Line \r;(v) Complete a Sign Diagram by doing a Sign Test on each interval \r;(vi) Determine Solution Set'),(323,'Quadratic Inequalities','C',6,'(a) Factorisable Quadratics: \r;Given a quadratic $$ax^2 + bx + c$$ with $$b^2 - 4ac > 0$$: \r;$$ax^2 + bx + c = a(x - \\frac{- b + \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a})(x - \\frac{- b - \\sqrt{b^2 - 4ac}}{2a})$$\r; \r;(b) Non-Factorisable Quadratics:  \r;Given a quadratic $$ax^2 + bx + c$$ with $$b^2 - 4ac < 0$$: $$b^2 - 4ac < 0$$ and $$a > 0$$:\r;(i) $$ax^2 + bx = c > 0 \\implies x \\in R$$ \r;(ii) $$ax^2 + bx = c < 0 \\implies x \\in \\{\\}$$'),(324,'Inequalities - Rational Functions','C',6,'For inequalities involving rational functions, the solution set must exclude all the Zero\'s of its Denominator.'),(325,'Solutions of Inequalities - Graphical Method','C',6,'Used to solve inequality of the form: $$f(x) > 0$$ or $$f(x) < 0$$ or of the form $$g(x) > h(x)$$'),(326,'Inequalities - Modulus Functions','C',6,'Given any real number $$k > 0$$: \r;(i) $$| x | < k \\implies -k < x < k$$ \r;(ii)$$| f(x) | < k \\implies -k < f(x) < k$$'),(327,'System of Linear Equations','C',7,'Using a graphical calculator, we can solve simultaneously for all unknowns using an Augmented Matrix. Any system of simultaneous linear equations will have one of the following: \r;(i) Unique solution \r;(ii) Infinitely many solutions \r;(iii) No solution.'),(328,'Binomial Theorem','F',8,'For any $$n \\in {Z}^{+}$$ : $$(a + b)^n = a^n  + na^{n-1}b + \\binom{n}{2}a^{n-2}b^2 + ..... + \\binom{n}{n-2}a^2b^{n-2} + \\binom{n}{n-1}ab^{n-1} + b^n$$ where $$\\binom{n}{r}a^{n-r}b^r$$ is called General Term of Expansion.'),(329,'Binomial Series','C',8,'For any $$n \\in Q$$ : $$(1 + x)^n = 1 + nx + \\frac{n(n-1)}{2!}x^2 + \\frac{n(n-1)(n-2}{3!}x^3 + ... + \\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)...(n-r+1)}{r!}x^r + ...$$  \r;If $$n \\in {Z}^{+}$$, then expansion is valid for all $$x \\in R$$ and has finite number of $$n + 1$$ terms.   \r;If $$n \\in Q$$ but $$n \\in {Z}^{+}$$, then expansion is valid only for $$| x | < 1: -1 < x < 1$$ and has infinite number of terms.'),(330,'Expansion in Ascending Powers of x','F',8,'$$(a + bx)^n = (a(1 + \\frac{bx}{a}))^n = a^n(1 + \\frac{bx}{a})^n = a^n(1 + n(\\frac{bx}{a}) + \\frac{n(n-1)}{2!}(\\frac{bx}{a})^2 + \\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)}{3!}(\\frac{bx}{a})^3 + ... )$$. This expansion is valid for $$|\\frac{bx}{a}| < 1 \\implies | x | < \\frac{a}{b} \\implies -\\frac{a}{b} < x < \\frac{a}{b}$$'),(331,'Expansion in Descending Powers of x','F',8,'$$(a + bx)^n = (bx(\\frac{a}{bx} + 1))^n = (bx)^n(1 + \\frac{a}{bx})^n = (bx)^n(1 + n(\\frac{a}{bx}) + \\frac{n(n-1)}{2!}(\\frac{a}{bx})^2 + \\frac{n(n-1)(n-2)}{3!}(\\frac{a}{bx})^3 + .... )$$. This expansion is valid for $$|\\frac{a}{bx}| < 1 \\implies | x | > \\frac{a}{b} \\implies x < -\\frac{a}{b}$$ or $$x > \\frac{a}{b}$$'),(332,'Binomial Series in Numerical Approximations','C',8,'In using the binomial series for numerical approximations, the value of $$x$$ must fall within the interval of convergence. \r;If the expansion is in ascending powers of $$x$$, the chosen value of $$x$$ must be as close to zero as possible: $$| x | < k $$, so that higher powers of $$x$$ are negligible. \r;If the expansion is in descending powers of $$x$$, the chosen value of $$x$$ should be as far away from zero as possible: $$| x | > k$$ so that higher powers of $$(\\frac{1}{x})$$ are negligible.'),(333,'Arithmetic Progression','F',9,'(i) General Form: $$a, a+d, a +2d, ... , a + (n-1)d , ...$$    \r;(ii) General Term $${T}_{n}$$: $${T}_{n} = a + (n - 1)d$$    \r;(iii) Common difference $$d$$: $$d = {T}_{n} - {T}_{n-1}$$    \r;(iv) Arithmetic Mean: $$\\frac{{T}_{n-1}+{T}_{n+1}}{2} = {T}_{n} \\implies  {T}_{n-1}+{T}_{n+1} = 2{T}_{n}$$    \r;(v) Sum of the first $$n$$ terms $${S}_{n}$$: $${S}_{n} = \\frac{n}{2}(2a + (n - 1)d)$$ or $${S}_{n} = \\frac{n}{2}(a + l)$$ where $$l = {T}_{n} = a + (n-1)d$$ '),(334,'Geometric Progression','F',9,'(i) General Form: $$a, ar, ar^2, ar^3, ... ,ar^{n-1}, ...$$  \r;(ii) General Term $${T}_{n}$$: $${T}_{n} = ar^{n-1}$$  \r;(iii) Common Ratio $$r$$ : $$r = \\frac{{T}_{n}}{{T}_{n-1}}$$  \r;(iv) Geometric Mean: $$\\sqrt{{T}_{n-1} \\times {T}_{n+1}} = {T}_{n} \\implies {T}_{n-1} \\times {T}_{n+1} = {{T}_{n}}^2$$  \r;(v) Geometric Series: $$a+ar+ar^2+ar^3+ ... + ar^{n-1} + ... $$  \r;(vi) Sum of the first n terms $${S}_{n}$$ : $${S}_{n} = \\frac{a(1-r^n)}{1-r}$$ or $$\\frac{a(r^n-1)}{r-1}$$'),(335,'Convergent Infinite Geometric Series','F',9,'$${S}_{\\infty}$$ exists and $${S}_{\\infty} = \\frac{a}{1 - r}$$'),(336,'General Infinite Geometric Series','C',9,'Given a general infinite geometric series: $$a+ar+ar^2+ar^3+...$$ \r;(i) $$| r | < 1 \\implies {S}_{\\infty}$$ exists and $${S}_{\\infty} = \\frac{a}{1-r}$$. We say that the series is Convergent.   \r;(ii)$$| r | > 1 \\implies {S}_{\\infty}$$ does not exist. We say that the series is Divergent.'),(337,'General Sequence and Series','F',9,'Given any series: $$S_{n} = {T}_{1} + {T}_{2} + {T}_{3} + ... + {T}_{n}$$ and $${S}_{n-1} = {T}_{1} + {T}_{2} + {T}_{3} + ... + {T}_{n-1}$$. Hence, $${T}_{n} = {S}_{n} - {S}_{n-1}$$'),(338,'AP or GP Determination','C',9,'(i) If $${T}_{n} - {T}_{n-1} = k$$ where $$k$$ is a constant independent of $$n$$, then the sequence is an AP with common difference $$d = k$$. \r;(ii) If $$\\frac{{T}_{n}}{{T}_{n-1}} = k$$ where $$k$$ is a constant independent of $$n$$, then the sequence is a GP with common ratio $$r = k$$. \r;(iii) If neither of the above occur, then the sequence is neither an AP or GP.'),(339,'Rules of Summation -